I"
<p>I had a great opportunity to talk about data ethics in practice at the <a href="https://www.scotlandis.com/blog/events/scotsoft-2020/">ScotSoft2020</a> conference. I decided this would be the perfect chance to try out the amazing <a href="https://revealjs.com/">reveal.js</a> html presentation framework.</p>

<p>Iâ€™ve tried plenty of different ways to create presentations (like <a href="https://office.live.com/start/powerpoint.aspx">powerpoint</a>, <a href="https://bookdown.org/yihui/rmarkdown/ioslides-presentation.html">Rmarkdown</a>, <a href="https://www.google.co.uk/slides/about/">google slides</a> and <a href="https://www.latextemplates.com/cat/presentations">LaTeX</a>) and Iâ€™m always keen to try out new (ideally <a href="https://opensource.com/resources/what-open-source">open-source</a>) tools.</p>

<p>The <a href="https://revealjs.com/">reveal.js</a> framework represents a wacky new way to create presentations - by writing them directly in <a href="https://www.w3schools.com/html/html_intro.asp"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">html</code></a> and it is completely free and open-source!!ðŸŽ‰</p>

<p>Here are the <a href="https://josephcrispell.github.io/standalone/data-ethics-in-practice/index.html">slides</a> I put together:</p>
